text: The person who's going to say the blessing is Benny Shendo, who's the director of our American Indian program here at Stanford, and he's Hamas. I'm going to say the opening prayer in my own language, so also, as I say the prayer, you can say your own prayer as well. . . . . . . . . . . Okay, I guess we're going to go ahead and get started, so everyone can be seated and find a seat. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . supposed to be like a conversation the way it's going to work is each each person who's going to talk about their work is going to come and sit at this point in the table mainly because we are videotaping the event and we'll present for about 10 minutes and then the rest of the time will be for basically a conversation just to talk about you know the issues that were brought up in the presentation maybe some similar experiences we've had doing doing research just you know very informal you know we want people to feel comfortable and just just really enjoy the day we're going to start out with Benny Shendo who's going to come up and say a few words and then after you Benny Shendo will be Jim Larimore who's used to be the director of our American Indian program office but now the acting dean of students here at the university again I just like to welcome all of you to the second annual research forum as Rania mentioned I'm the assistant dean of students and also director of our American Indian program I'm new to Stanford I've been here for going on my seventh month but it's it's been really good when Gil mentioned this forum last year they had their their first annual really got me excited because it's one of the things that we really wanted to do is what are some of our students doing in terms of scholarship and work that affect native communities And so we talked about it, and we began to brainstorm it. We did it last year. It was very informal, and it was a wonderful experience. We wanted to keep it that way. We wanted it to be a conversation, a discussion, so that we could really get a lot out of it. And so we planned it, and Renia has been very—both Renia and Gail have been very instrumental in making this happen again. So I'd just like to welcome all of you on behalf of our American Indian and Alaska Native program at Stanford. So I hope you enjoy your day. I guess this is kind of an unusual thing for me because, as Renia mentioned, I've been kind of changing my professional identities around Stanford for the last year or so. And I've made a series of shifts. And the shifts that I've made— the first that have come have been after serving for nine years as the director for the American Indian program, making a break and starting full-time as a doctoral student over in the School of Education in higher ed and administration and policy analysis last fall. And after six months of being a student, taking a leave and stepping in as the acting dean of students here, and after my first week on the job, which was just this past week— I can't tell you how much I'm looking forward to going back to being a student again in September— and just getting much more into it. Getting much more in touch with kind of classroom life, with research, and with a chance to really focus on thinking hard about things, on kind of how things are, how they got that way, and maybe how they could be. And so this is, for me, a little bit of a homecoming in being back involved with the community after trying to maintain a little bit of distance to help my own transition this year. And so it's a real honor. It's a real kind of honor and a pleasure to be among all the folks that are here this morning. I spoke yesterday afternoon with Condoleezza Rice, our university provost, and it was then that she informed me that she had a scheduling conflict that had come up with a gathering up in San Francisco. And so Condie asked me if I would extend a welcome on behalf of the university to folks that have traveled from other schools, other places here in California and elsewhere to be with us today. And so I hope that, and it looks from looking out behind the camera and out the window, that this may be the kind of Stanford weather and kind of Northern California weather that we're accustomed to here. And so I hope that the surroundings will be pleasant and supportive of the kind of thinking and talking that you all want to try and do today. As Benny was doing his opening prayer for this gathering this morning, I just wanted to say a few words of how important it is that as people gather that we pray, and as we pray that we pray for wisdom, among other things, and that the wisdom that we seek is in order to make life better for those around us, to make life better for those among us, and also to try and make life better for those yet to come. And I think that, for me, represents the spirit of what American Indian and Alaska Native research is about. We have been researchers and scholars. For thousands of years. And it may not have been things that have been written down and recorded in the forms that universities are used to, but I think you can find no better example of scholarship and humane scholarship than the kind of knowledge that exists within our communities, the kind of knowledge that people are about working with and creating and passing on. And so I want to say, again, on behalf of myself and for the university, that this is an important gathering. And that this marks, I think, a real turning point for the way that we can support each other and the way that we can support students and support faculty, tenured and otherwise, in the pursuits and the kinds of pressures that they face in their lives. As people go through the day, what I would like to suggest or offer as a way of thinking about this is that people realize that this is a time, some of you may have met each other, you may have come with friends from other campuses, but this is a real opportunity to get to know people that you may come in contact with on an infrequent basis, people that you may not see until maybe during Palo season. You'll see folks around different places, faces that you might recognize in different parts of the country at different meetings or community gatherings. And so I hope that during the day you'll take the opportunity to get to know some folks that may not be from where you're from and get a chance to help establish a tighter community base for all of us that way. I would also like to suggest that maybe there are a few different ways to think about how this gathering is situated and what this represents because I think it's important to be able to look at this assembly of people and to look back at how this connects with our past and to think about how this connects you with previous generations within your own tribe, within your own communities, within the campus communities that you're a part of, within the whole idea of knowledge and what that represents for our communities. And so as you're here and as you're hopefully going through some of the excitement about thinking about things that people are going to present, you'll be able to feel some connection with those that have been here before you. I also hope that you'll feel a sense of that connection with the people that are here with you today and that as you listen to people and engage in some discussions with each other that you'll be able to do that in a friendly, cooperative, but even challenging way with each other and to really help push each other to the best and the hardest thinking that you can do about things. And finally, which kind of brings me back to my old life, being I think more involved on a regular basis with the community here, I really hope that you'll carry some things away from this weekend that are going to help you within your own communities and especially that are going to help you reach out to one more person, one more student, whether they're a very young kid, whether they're in elementary school or junior high or high school, whether they're on campus. Because the ultimate measure of how successful we are is going to be how much we're able to do to bring more people along with us. And so the knowledge, the kind of energy that you pick up today, I hope sustains you in your own activities, but I hope also helps you in your work as a community leader, as someone who has influence, as someone whose actions and thoughts and words carry a great deal of power. And so with that, I just want to say thanks to all of you for making the trip here. Early on a Saturday morning, when I know that you've all been no doubt working hard on other things and we're getting up early this morning, may not have been kind of what your original intention had been some time ago. We're just glad to have you here. And one final thing for, I guess I'll pass this along to Raina, is as the day goes on, you may find that you're in need of a break or something a little bit different. And so given that this is research, and I think sometimes people have, fairly defined, rigid conceptions of research, I wanted to bring along a piece of poetry that was written by an Osage writer and poet named Dwayne Big Eagle, who has a poem entitled, My Grandfather Was a Quantum Physicist, that some of you may be familiar with. And so if there's a break and you need something a little kind of interesting and scholarly in a different way, I hope that this might be a benefit to you as well. Anyway, that's it. That's as long-winded as I can get speaking for me and the provost. And anyway, welcome. I'm glad that you're all here. Thanks, Jim. What we wanted to do also is if the professors who brought students, if they could introduce their students, you know, their name and their field and all that kind of thing. So we're going to go ahead and get started. So I'm going to let the professor from James here do the introductions. Let me just stand up for a minute so I can see everybody. I'm very glad to be here again this year. I'm kind of reflecting as we begin this day on what we did last year. And it occurs to me that we've doubled in several ways. We've doubled in terms of the number of schools that are represented here. I think last year it was just Stanford and UC Santa Cruz. And this year we've got people from Mills College and UC Berkeley is here too. Is that right? So we're up to four schools in this area. That's exciting. We've doubled in the size of the room. That's always encouraging. We wouldn't have had enough room if we'd been back in that old space. And I've noticed too that we've doubled in the amount that Gil Ramirez is eating so far. I owed you one there. I had heard a lot of good things over the years about Jim Larimore, and it's been really nice to get a chance to meet him here this morning. And I feel like I've learned some things already. Although I'd heard what a wonderful person he was, I didn't realize how wise and knowledgeable he is, because he said everything that I wanted to say. So I know he must be wise and knowledgeable. He said a lot of good things for us to keep in mind, and I don't have too much, nor should I really add, to what he said. I do think this is an unusual event. I think that each one of us can think back in our own lives in whatever stage of the educational process that we may be in, and I mean the kind of restricted, institutional, formal kind of things, that we may be in. I think the kind of institutional, formal kind of education that most of us in this room are involved in in one way or another is other kinds of education, other kinds of knowledge that maybe aren't as widely recognized as such by a lot of people, as Jim has suggested. But certainly we can all think about our experiences in the educational institutions and realize that an event like this is a pretty unusual occurrence, or we can just come together in what has appropriately been called a research forum for American Indians, without having to defend the legitimacy of the kinds of concerns and questions and topics that we are concerned with before any kind of wider audience. So we can come together and talk to each other. That doesn't mean we all think alike. It doesn't mean that we all are going to approach any given issue in the same way, but that we can really come into this room and this space with a sense of community, of community. Of mutual understanding and respect and concern and have a meaningful conversation. We can say some things, talk about our own specific projects, and also have a chance to learn from each other. I think one of the real ways in which the educational system fails us is when it creates a competitive environment that says that your worth is dependent on your GPA or the comments that the teacher writes on your paper or how you compare with other people. We know, I think, from a variety of different kinds of backgrounds, that that kind of basis for human worth is not real solid. It actually contributes to a lot of the kinds of problems that we see in our society and in our own lives. So I would just kind of call that to our attention this morning, that we can kind of come to this with a different frame of mind, with a different understanding about what a human being is and what the importance of human creativity is. That doesn't mean that we can't challenge each other, that we can't push each other to think about issues in ways that we haven't looked at. I know I want to be challenged. I'm unfortunately not going to be here for the whole day. I'm going to Duluth, Minnesota, where I'm going to participate in the Tribal Colleges Consortium Annual Conference, something I've been looking forward to very well for quite a long time. And I'm going to be giving kind of a workshop, not really going to make a presentation, so much as a workshop on some things that I've been working on in Santa Cruz. And mainly not because I think I have something to teach them, but because I want to hear what they have to say to me from the tribal college context, you know, what we do at UC Santa Cruz. So I think all of us can benefit from those kinds of feedback and critique. But that there's a way in which we can do that that builds us up as a community, that builds us up as individuals, rather than in a sense of that, well, I have to show that I'm sharper than this person or I've thought about this a little more than they have or that there's any kind of a competitive atmosphere. You know, we're all here for a reason. This forum's been facilitated and organized very well by Renia and Gil Ramirez, and we owe them a lot of thanks. And I hope at the end of the day that you'll, or throughout the day, that you'll have a chance to just express your appreciation for their work on this. But they've brought each of you here, you know, for a reason. And so there's nobody here that has to prove that they have a right to be here or that they have something to say. We're all kind of in this together, if you will. So I'm just going to stop there and maybe suggest a little bit about process. One of the ways we do have to sort of accommodate to the kinds of rules and regulations, we've come to know on the institution, has to do with the problem of time. And that is we've got a lot of people with a lot of good things to say here. And I know if we were maybe out at a community event or at an annual pow-wow or a festival of some type, maybe we could put our watches away. But for the purposes of getting everyone a chance to speak, we are going to have to monitor the time just a little bit. So I'm going to, at least for the morning, I'll be gone. In the afternoon, you can handle it as you like. But for the morning, I think I'll just sit up here and I'll probably prompt people when they get to about the 10-minute mark with a slip of paper and then give them about two more minutes just to wrap it up. And then we'll go from there into time of question and answer and really be thinking about engaging and listening actively, not just listening passively, but what's really being said and what's significant about what's going on here and what might you be able to contribute. We'll also try to keep the questions to a fairly short period or a fairly short format. If you want to make a speech, talk to Rennie and she'll put you on the program. But if you just want to add another angle of thinking about something or ask a question, that would be the appropriate way. And we'll try to get as many people involved in that dialogue as possible. In fact, I was also going to suggest if there's a couple people in the back tables who want to move up to these two seats in the front here, there's still a couple open if you want to be part of this closer circle here. I just wanted to add that I asked Robert if he could help facilitate the question and answer. So if you want to say something, just kind of look at Robert and maybe just make a sign or something, and then he can kind of help with that. Do you want to move up here? Yeah. Anybody else that wants to just make a comment before we get going here or a response of any type to the opening comments? The other thing I wanted to do, just before we began, is which I wanted to go around the room and make sure everyone just said their name, their tribe, and their school. So I don't know. Maybe start back here. Platt, Lansley, Ojibwe. Jim Laramore, still from Stanford Conventions. Lloyd Lee. From Stanford. Kenny Woodward. from Stanford. Jill Leveris. from Stanford. from Stanford. from Stanford. from Stanford. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . I'm Larry Gross, I'm from Minnesota Chippewa, right now I'm at Smith College in North Hampton, Massachusetts. I've come a long way for this symposium. Yeah, if at the end of the day you feel like it wasn't good, see Tina about getting your money back. She'll be glad to help you out. Not on the flight, just the registration. Okay, well let's begin then. Oh, I'm sorry. Yes, Gil? I just wanted to say, for those people that are not from here, kind of an important thing to know. The bathrooms are downstairs. The men's bathroom is right below here. And the women's bathroom is down the hall. Anyone else? Okay, we'll go ahead and get started then. It's my pleasure to introduce our first presenter from UC Santa Cruz. Terri Greaves is Kiowa. She's listed as History of Consciousness, which is sort of wishful thinking on somebody's part, not mine. She's actually in American Studies. I wish I could convince her to stay. I wish I could convince her to stick around and be a grad student at ISKCON so I could continue to work with her. But she's a graduating senior, and she's teaching a student-directed seminar this quarter, which is her last quarter, titled Indians, Redskins, Bucks, and Squaws, Images of Indians in American Popular Culture, which just started on Wednesday. She's only had one meeting. She's going to talk to us about her research, which she's been working on for a year or so, that went into the course, and then talk about her course design and some of the things — the kinds of methodological and theoretical issues that that raises. And I think it's a topic that we all can relate to at some level, and hopefully will provoke some good discussion that may actually feed into her course, too. So, Terri? Well, like you said, I'm teaching this class, and, well, I guess I'm going to be a little more autobiographical than she is. I'm theoretical. But the reason why I started this — this class was going to be my thesis. And the reason why I started looking into images of Indians is because my mom owned an Indian arts and crafts store on Wind River Reservation in Wyoming. And my entire life, all the money that we've survived off of has come from selling Indian things. And has come from... Consumers' want of those Indian things, and that identity. And I remember being a little girl, and my mother always used to keep our hair in braids. And we used to play in front of the store, and the white tourists would ask us for photographs, and sometimes they'd give us money for it, and sometimes they wouldn't. But we thought it was all fun and good, and, you know, we'd get like five bucks out of the deal. And basically I guess they would come to the reservation on their way to Yellowstone Park to see Indians, and they saw us. Which was sort of funny because we're Kiowa and Comanche. We're not Shoshone or Arapahoe from the reservation, you know. And so part of what my mother does is she sells herself along with the arts and crafts. She dresses sort of like the old ladies on the reservation dress. And she's always dressed like that from as long as I can remember, like before I was born. And that is one of the biggest selling points to the things that she sells in her store. She's now in Santa Fe. And last summer when I was in Santa Fe visiting, I was hanging out in the store with her, and she was standing there. And my mother's like, you know, 60 now. And she was standing there, and this white woman came in and saw her and thought she was just the cutest thing in the world and ran right over to her and grabbed ahold of her braids and sort of yanked on them like and said, oh, you're so cute, you're so cute. And I remember like looking at that and just being obviously like appalled and wanting to hit this woman. But my mom, who's like deals with this on a daily basis, was very composed and said to her, please don't touch my hair. And I saw over this woman's face a sudden realization that she was dealing with a human being and not a doll. Not this cute little Indian woman to be fondled or touched or bought or whatever. And I don't know. So that's what's led me to look into these, to look into what we're seen as and how we create ourselves the way that my mother has created herself. Because in a way, she's brought this upon herself. I mean, she could dress like a white person and blend in. And she doesn't. She sticks herself out. And she doesn't. She just doesn't do what she does. And she just does. And I'm really, really, really proud of her and that she's doing this work in her own way. And I'm really, really proud. And she's doing a really good job of it because again, no one's paid her much attention. And she's doing it for survival. And it's more than just ... it's more than just survival of money. It's cultural survival also. And so, let's see. So I've been working on this research for like almost two years now. And I've come up with this really huge bibliography. Part of it is annotated and part of it is unannotated. The last six pages are unannotated. It's all information, books, periodicals, articles, films that I've come up with that all deal with this issue in one way or another. And I'd be happy to give this out. I'd really like this information to get out there. I hold no claim to it at all. The more people who look at it and think about it, the better. And the one thing that I found, and the way that I structured my course was, is there's two approaches to Indian images and Indian identity on the outside. And the first one comes from a white perspective, which looks at the images as created by white people and imposed. And then there's, in the last, I'd say, maybe even ten years, not even that long, there's a whole bunch of Indian research. And Indian writing and thinking that sees Indian identity as, that we have agency in creating our Indian identity. The way that my mother dresses up and sells herself. And so, what was I going to say? Oh, one of the films that I'm looking at is by a Hopi filmmaker. His name is Victor Mora. I'm probably totally slaughtering that name. But he did this film called Imagining Indians. And it's an excellent film. And it brings up issues that, for Native Americans, which is not a lot. Most of what I found doesn't bring up those issues for Native Americans. And what he writes about, or what he visually shows, is Indians dealing with this thing of having, you know, this thing of having responsibility for what we allow to be consumed. What we allow to be commodified. And one of the things that he talks about is sacred items that are now for sale. Or sacred items that have been turned into tourist items, like pipe bags or something like that. And how we help that. We help in losing the sacred of our communities by doing that. By allowing things to be commodified. And it's something that I personally have a lot of interest in because I'm a beadworker. It's like I haven't had a real job for the last, I don't know, five or six years. And I've made most of my money in the last few years on beadwork. And what I create holds huge implications. What I decide to allow to be sold. The designs I decide to use. It can be extremely appropriative. And a really sticky situation the more I think about it. So he talks about, Victor Masayeswa talks about this responsibility that we have as Indian people to our own identity. And keeping the sacred sacred. And using our good judgment. Using, not letting money talk all the time. And it's a really difficult lesson for me to learn because I'm poor. And I really need the money. But, I don't know. Let's see. I don't know what else to say about this. I'm teaching this class. Most of the students in my class are white. And I don't think that we're going to get into those issues that I would like to get into. And they're really issues that maybe only Indians can talk about. Because it's our identity that's at stake. And we're the ones that need to take control over the theorizing and the writing that's done on who we are. And what our image is to the public. And I don't know. I think I'm going to stop there because I could go into like greater detail about things. Like particulars that I found out about images. But, you know, that might be boring. Thanks, Sherry. Are there questions people had right off the bat? We'll start with you. You used two terms in your presentation, sacred and culture. How would you define those terms? Geez. Well, I can only answer personally. I don't know how else to answer. And I can only answer from experience. And identity is such a twisted thing in America. And it has to do with race. And for Indians, it has to do with blood quantum. And for me, my understanding is I've seen Indians that aren't really Indians. You know what I mean? Blood quantum. They're not recognized. And it's the culture that ends up ultimately defining how they're received by their communities. And so, in a way, I think that culture. Do I sound like an anthropologist? I don't know. Maybe I do. But I think that culture really defines a great deal of our identity, obviously. And what was the other term? Sacred. Sacred. Now, that's really sticky. That's, like, terribly sticky. Well, the way that Victor was using it in this film was those things that are central to our identity. And those things that are central to our identity can be seen as culture. They can also be seen as a form of culture. They can be seen as a form of faith or religion. I don't like the word religion. It seems too institutional. I like the word faith better because it can come in any form. And I think that they're sacred for all people, not just Indians, obviously. And I don't know. I guess that's how I define it. I don't know if that answered your question. Teacher, I have a question. When you're teaching in this group of white students there, are you getting the sense from them that they're reinforcing those ideas about objectifying Indians as a cultural commodity? Are you trying to undo it? Do you see that coming from them? Are they wanting to take that and, again, go out and learn enough to, again, follow that path? I've only had one class meeting, so I can't tell you. I know. It's kind of an unfair question. It's terrible. But just even thinking about it because I always teach in classes that I've heard now with white students as opposed to these students. Yeah. Well, you know, my hope is that I won't be reinforcing the stereotypes. And I think that the strategy that I'm going to use is to constantly refer back to myself because I'm a living model, right? Standing in front of them, breathing in front of them. And I have these stories. Hopefully they won't get boring. Hopefully they won't get bored by them. But I have all these stories of what, how, I mean, my mom's in the art business. And the art business is all about identity. It's all about image. I mean, image is the first thing that sells. The art comes later. And if I can in some way use my life as an example to show them maybe insights that they're not going to get by reading, you know, there's a really excellent book called The White Man's Indian. I'm sure you know it. Burke Offer. And you can't get that from Burke Offer. You know what I mean? It comes from a different perspective. So I just hope by just physically being there is going to, like, push it, push the issue past those stereotypes. I don't know if it's going to work or not. I've heard all kinds of horror stories about how it doesn't work. So we'll see. You want to talk about how your course design addresses this issue as well in terms of the first half and the second half, the films you're using? Yeah. The first half of the course is all work written by non-Indians. And the film, I'm only showing one film, is Thunderheart. And they're all, they come from the white perspective. And some of them, it's just, some of it's really excellent work. And I really appreciate that. Some of it is very controversial. And I really appreciate that, too. And hopefully in the class we can see how controversial and how almost, like, polar opposite it is from the Indian-created writing and analysis, which is the second half of the course. And I'm using three films. They're all films by Indian people. Navajo Talking Pictures, Imagining Indians, and Herald of Orange. And I think, in particular, Imagining Indians and Herald of Orange are, like, really good. Like, they, when I watched Imagining Indians for the first time, I was like, yes, this is exactly what I want to try to get across in my course, this film. And if they can understand that film by the end of the class, I'll be really happy. I'll be really happy I'll have succeeded. I think you answered my question right now in helping to deal with issues of identity. It seems like you have two audiences, a couple audiences, one mostly for Indians and one for non-Indians as well. And so I was wondering in the class how you can, I think part of that would involve changing attitudes and stuff like that. I was wondering how you can do that, how you can make that powerful, how you can encourage it. Right. I think you made a great answer to my question. Thank you. Thank you. The class is a discussion class. It is not a lecture class. I cannot imagine myself lecturing. Like, that just seems really foreign to me. So, and the other thing that I have going for me is I'm a student. I'm totally equal level. I don't have an office. I don't have, you know, a super, like, professor's box at the steno pool or whatever. Well, actually, that's not true. I do. But anyway, it's like a lecture. It's like almost a level playing field that I'm coming from that professors don't have. And I hope that, I mean, when we're out in the real world, isn't that when we connect with another person, when we really connect, it's when we feel like we're on a level playing field, when we can really hear what they're saying. So I'm hoping that that's going to come through. I don't know. We'll see. At the end of the quarter, when I'm not graduating, because my class is a total failure, we'll see. When my students hate my guts. I think I'm taking the hard line. I just wanted to ask you if you have any questions, you know, from your experience, if you might want to ask, pose any questions here, since we have all kind of different people here in the room with the wide points of view. Well, I don't know. I guess my question would be, I keep coming back to this film by Victor Masayesva, which it just, it's an incredible film, and I recommend it to anyone, everyone. And he shows this scene of these paintings on a rock wall, and he's talking about, like, looking back through time, how once we used to make these things for survival, for life, and then somewhere along the line, money started to be exchanged for these items. And then somewhere along the line, after that, we stopped claiming responsibility for that whole process of exchange for survival, maybe not seeing it, or seeing it in the same light, or not seeing it in the same light. And I just wonder, like, I mean, that's, like I said, it's, like, a really difficult question for me to deal with, like, my own responsibility to what I do, to the art that I do. And, but at the same instance, I do feel this responsibility to the sacred, whatever the heck that is, I don't know. And I don't know. I guess my question is, what do people think about that? I mean, it's, of course, I think, like, people have always, Indian people have always done that, but to a certain extent, like, with the, I can see it in the movie industry better than in any other industry, is Indian film stars walking into roles that maybe are not the best roles to be walking into, and doing it for money, and then not liking to hear any criticism of them coming from the Indian community for doing that, and saying, oh, well, the Indian community is poor, and this is a way that I'm getting out of it. But in a way, it compromises our identity. Can I just add something to that based on some conversations that we've had in my office that she hasn't quite said it this way, but I think some of the things that I've learned from Teri in terms of the questions that she's asking, that she's posing to the people in this room, is that it's one thing for us to stand up, and lament the commodification of Indian culture, or the appropriations, the inappropriate appropriations committed in the name of New Age spirituality, and on down the list, but what happens when we acknowledge that Indian people, both today and in the past, have been active participants?
